[2]
Date: Thu, 10 Apr 1997 14:05:15 +0930
From: "Carman, Judy (SAHC)" <Carman.judy@health.sa.gov.au>
Subject: Salmonella in Australia
Marguerite Wegner has correctly identified [in a previous posting. MHJ] a
perception in the general community that Victoria has a real problem in
food-borne disease. I have also seen this written in Australia's newspapers.
This has been largely based on comparing the (higher) numbers of reports of
food-borne disease coming out of Victoria recently with the (lower) numbers
of reports coming out of other states of the country.
I would like to make 3 points.
Firstly, not surprisingly, the number of Salmonella outbreaks tend to peak
in summer in Australia. We had a number in South Australia, a few weeks
before Victoria had their lot.
Secondly, only some clusters make the newspapers. These tend to be the ones
that require public warnings or public recalls of foodstuffs. Other states
may have had clusters that have been successfully investigated, that the
public may not be aware of.
Finally, and most importantly, although I don't have the figures, I doubt
that Victoria would have a higher rate of food-borne disease notifications
per capita than the rest of the country. What they do have are a group of
people who are very good at finding clusters in the mass of data that comes
into them. Then they are very good at determining a food that caused the
cluster of cases. In short, because they are good at their job, they are
generating a lot of (often adverse) publicity. The public is then looking at
the number of their successes and is interpreting it as a systemic problem
in food-borne disease in the state.
---
Dr. Judy Carman
Senior Epidemiologist
Communicable Disease Control Branch
South Australian Health Commission
carman.judy@health.sa.gov.au
