[3]
Date: Thu, 10 Apr 1997 10:04:21 +0930
From: "Rose, Nick (SAHC)" <Rose.nick@health.sa.gov.au>
Subject: Salmonella infections - Australia Victoria
The Victorian Department of Human Services have advised that there were 822
reported cases of salmonellosis in 1996. In the smaller state of South
Australia a typical year results in 200-500 reported cases. There would be
many times more cases not reported and it can be safely concluded that
salmonellosis is a common infection with many thousands of cases occurring
around Australia each year. As has long been the case. If we take away the
ONE major incident in Victoria (bread rolls with 500+ reported cases) the
number of cases in the other Victorian outbreaks is scarcely significant
against the national or even the Victorian background. Against this
background it wouldn't take much of a cranking up of the epidemiology
investigations, anywhere, to uncover more outbreaks - especially in a
situation where exceptionally hot weather could increase the risk of food
poisoning.
So rather than ask what is wrong with the Victorian food safety system a
more logical question is to ask what is so good about the Victorian system
for uncovering outbreaks? Of course a better approach would be to ask
questions about how to deal with the thousands of background cases
experienced nationally. This is currently being addressed, at an industry
level at least, with national proposals for HACCP-based QA systems.
---
Brian Delroy
Manager, Food Section
South Australian Health Commission
