> SALMONELLA INFECTIONS - AUSTRALIA (VICTORIA) (04)
RE: Salmonella infections and temperature, supporting Oz:
UK reports that 16% of foodborne infection explosions (= 2 or more patients
involved) are caused "at home". Most problems caused by:
-- poultry
-- desserts
-- meat
-- meatproducts
Most important risk-factors turned out to be (in order of importance):
-- keeping too long time at too high temperature
-- insufficient heating
-- crosscontamination
Most important pathogen involved
-- Salmonella enteritidis 57%
-- Salmonella (other species) 20%
Reported source (in "Nieuwbrief VoedselVeiligheid", April 1997): Comm. Dis.
Report, review number 13, 6-Dec-1996.
A consciousness-raising INQUIRY:
It would be interesting if promed readers would report to me the highest and
lowest measured temperature in their own refrigerator at home.
My own refrigerator, because of its construction (cooled vertical wall at
the back):
>>>> Highest shelf= 12 degC (for beverages)
>>>> Lowest shelf = 3 degC (for meat, milk)
The problem may be that you need 2 thermometers at the same time..
Please fill in your own data and send them back to
>>>>> javr@pi.net
I will report a summary to promed.
